ce:section.ce:para:
The 17O NMR spectra obtained from the [C2O1mpyr][FSI] IL and its mixtures with LiFSI (Fig. 2
                        ) confirm the feasibility of acquiring good quality spectra in reasonable experimental time frames (around 4 h each) at a standard magnetic field strength (11.7 T), particularly at higher sample temperatures. As shown in Fig. 2, the neat [C2O1mpyr][FSI] and with 20 mol% and 50 mol% LiFSI display distinguishable 17O peaks from the [C2O1mpyr] cation and [FSI] anion across a range of temperatures. Similarly, the ILs with NaFSI at varying salt concentrations exhibit distinct 17O NMR spectra as shown in Fig. S3. Although the 17O NMR peaks have broad widths in comparison to 1H, 19F, 13C, and 7Li NMR spectra, the spectra have adequate signal-to-noise (S/N) ratios and resolution to reveal the inequivalent 17O nuclei and to allow accurate measurements of their δs and LWs, at least at higher temperatures. The effect of temperature on the LWs of 17O NMR are discussed in more detail below, but the peaks can be seen to narrow significantly at higher temperatures in all cases, reflecting the increased molecular dynamics and improving the experimental sensitivity. Other ether-functionalized ILs are also amenable to 17O NMR as shown in Fig. 3
                        .
